1. Recalling your exciting statistical discoveries on penguin flipper length relationship to sex, species, and island, you decide to make some publication quality figures to demonstrate your findings. Use the ggplot2 package to make the graphs and the palmerpenguins package for the penguins data.

1A. Begin by creating a violin plot with sex on the x axis and flipper length on the y axis. The violin blobs fill color should differ between the two sexes (default colors are fine!).

# load packages
library(palmerpenguins)
library(ggplot2)

# subset penguins data to include only penguins with recorded sex
peng_df <- subset(penguins, !is.na(sex))

# create a violin plot visualizing sex and flipper length data and assign it to an object
peng_plot <- ggplot(data = peng_df, mapping = aes(x = sex, y = flipper_length_mm, fill = sex)) +
  geom_violin()

# load plot
peng_plot

1B. That graph was a fine first pass but you realize youve neglected to include penguin species information in the graph! Facet the graph to divide the plot into three panels (either rows or columns are fine)one panel per species of penguin. Also, remove the gray background color (but keep the black axis lines!) and add custom axis titles that remove the underscores in the raw column names.

# update the plot to remove background, keep axis lines and add axis titles
peng_plot2 <- peng_plot +
  facet_grid(.~ species) +
   labs(x = "Sex", y = "Flipper Length (mm)") +
   theme(panel.grid = element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_blank(), 
        axis.line = element_line(color = "black"))

# load updated plot
peng_plot2

2. Remembering your colleagues suggestion of evaluating the effect of island you decide to make a second graph where you visualize penguin flipper length at the three islands.

2A. Create a violin plot where island is on the y axis and flipper length is on the x axis. Make the fill color of each violin different between islands. Remove the gray background color, keep black axis lines, and customize the axis titles so this graph visually matches your first graph.

# create violin plot visualizing islands and flipper length, and customize it similar to the first graph
island_plot <- ggplot(data = peng_df, mapping = aes(x = flipper_length_mm , y = island, fill = island)) +
  geom_violin() +
   labs(x = "Flipper Length (mm)", y = "Island") +
   theme(panel.grid = element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_blank(), 
        axis.line = element_line(color = "black"))

# load plot
island_plot

2B. After making this graph you realize you are accidentally re-using the default ggplot2 red and blue colors. This could be very confusing to your audience so you definitely need to address it. Visit the Coolors website (coolors.co/palettes/trending) and pick a custom color for each of the three islands. Manually set the violin fill to give each island one of these three colors.

# update plot to include custom colors
island_plot2 <- island_plot +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Biscoe" = "#355C7D", "Dream" = "#F67280", "Torgersen" = "#6C5B7B"))

# load updated plot
island_plot2

3. Your two graphs are looking great! Now you just need to combine them into one file for ease of sharing to your peers. Use the cowplot package to put both graphs (the species by sex graph and the island graph) into one plot. These can be either side-by-side or one on top of the other depending on your preference.

# load package
library(cowplot)

# combine both updated plots side-by-side into one plot
cowplot::plot_grid(island_plot2, peng_plot2, ncol = 2, nrow = 1)
